{"title_page": "William Foster Barham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n'''William Foster Barham''' (22 October 1802 \u2013 28 January 1845) was an English poet.\n\nBarham was the third son of [[Thomas Foster Barham (musician)|Thomas Barham Foster]]. He was born at [[Marazion]], in [[Cornwall]], 22 October 1802. He was educated in the grammar schools of [[Bodmin]] and [[Leeds]], and then proceeded to [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=BRN820WF|name=Barham, William Foster}}</ref> He won the [[Porson Prize]] in 1821 and 1822, and graduated B.A. in 1824 as twenty-second senior optime, second in the first class of the classical tripos, and second chancellor's medallist. He went out M.A. in 1827. His death occurred in [[Kent]] on 28 January 1845.<ref>Venn. The ''[[Dictionary of National Biography|DNB]]'' gives his date of death only as 'about 1847'.</ref>\n\nHe was the author of an unpublished poem on ''Moskow''. His Greek versions of portions of ''[[Othello]]'' and ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius C\u00e6sar]]'' are printed in a volume of ''Translations which have obtained the Porson Prize from 1817 to 1856'', 2nd edit., Camb. 1857, pp.&nbsp;16\u201323.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{DNB|wstitle=Barham, William Foster}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barham, William Foster}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Marazion]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{england-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n'''William Foster Barham''' (22 October 1802 \u2013 28 January 1845) was an English poet.\n\nBarham was the third son of [[Thomas Foster Barham (musician)|Thomas Barham Foster]]. He was born at [[Marazion]], in [[Cornwall]], 22 October 1802. He was educated in the grammar schools of [[Bodmin]] and [[Leeds]], and then proceeded to [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=BRN820WF|name=Barham, William Foster}}</ref> He won the [[Porson Prize]] in 1821 and 1822, and graduated B.A. in 1824 as twenty-second senior optime, second in the first class of the classical tripos, and second chancellor's medallist. He went out M.A. in 1827. His death occurred in [[Kent]] on 28 January 1845.<ref>Venn. The ''[[Dictionary of National Biography|DNB]]'' gives his date of death only as 'about 1847'.</ref>\n\nHe was the author of an unpublished poem on ''Moskow''. His Greek versions of portions of ''[[Othello]]'' and ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius C\u00e6sar]]'' are printed in a volume of ''Translations which have obtained the Porson Prize from 1817 to 1856'', 2nd edit., Camb. 1857, pp.&nbsp;16\u201323.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{DNB|wstitle=Barham, William Foster}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barham, William Foster}}\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:People from Marazion]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{england-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Foster_Barham"}
{"title_page": "Simcha Jacobovici", "text_new": "{{cleanup|reason=general standards|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        =Simcha Jacobovici\n|image       =SimchaJacobovici-002.JPG\n|alt         =\n|caption     =\n|birth_date  ={{Birth date and age|1953|04|04}}\n|birth_place =[[Petah Tikva]], [[Israel]]\n|death_date  =<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n|death_place =\n|nationality =[[Canadian nationality law|Canadian]] / [[Israeli nationality law|Israeli]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   =\n|education   = [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[McGill University]]<br>[[Master of Arts|M.A.]], [[University of Toronto]]\n|occupation  =Film director, producer, journalist, writer\n}}\n'''Simcha Jacobovici''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u026a|m|x|\u0259|_|j|\u0259|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|b|o\u028a-|v|\u026a|t\u0283}}; born April 4, 1953 in [[Petah Tikva]], [[Israel]]) is an [[Israeli Canadians|Israeli-Canadian]] multi award-winning film director, producer, freelance journalist, and ''New York Times'' bestselling author.\n\n==Biography==\nSimcha Jacobovici's parents were from [[Ia\u0219i]], [[Romania]].<ref>[http://www.libertatea.ro/ultima-ora/sicriul-lui-iisus-opera-unui-roman-180286 'Sicriul lui Iisus', opera unui roman], 27 February 2007, ''Libertatea'', Retrieved 19 February 2017</ref> He was born April 4, 1953, in Petach Tikvah, Israel. In 1962, the family relocated to Canada.\n\nHe earned a B.A. in Philosophy and Political Science (with honors) from [[McGill University]] and an M.A. in International Relations from the [[University of Toronto]]. {{asof|2015}} he was an [[Adjunct Professor]] of Religious Studies at [[Huntington University (Canada)|Huntington University]],<ref name=huntington>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114853/http://www.huntingtonu.ca/faculty/simcha-jacobovici| title=Simcha Jacobovici - Huntington University| work=Huntington University| accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref> in Greater Sudbury, Ontario. He is married and the father of five children.\n\n==Film career==\n\nJacobovici is a three time [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] winner for Outstanding Investigative Journalism<ref name=emmyonline>{{cite web| url=http://www.emmyonline.org/mediacenter/news_28th_nominees_data_list.html| title=The Emmy Awards - 27th Annual News & Documentary Emmy Awards| work=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences| accessdate=November 4, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220155142/http://www.emmyonline.org/mediacenter/news_28th_nominees_data_list.html| archivedate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=playbackonline>{{cite web| url=http://playbackonline.ca/1997/09/22/19286-19970922/| title=The importance of winning Emmy(s)| last=Maddever| first=Mary| work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]| date=November 22, 1997| accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and a ''[[New York Times]]'' bestselling author.<ref name=newyorktimeslist>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/18/books/bestseller/0318besthardnonfiction.html?_r=0| title=Hardcover Nonfiction - The New York Times| work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 18, 2007| accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> l His filmmaking awards also include a certificate of Special Merit from the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], a Gold Medal from the International Documentary Festival of [[Nyon]], two US [[CableACE Award]]s,<ref name=ace1>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1997/tv/news/cableace-awards-111661098/|title=CableAce Awards - Variety| work=Variety Media, LLC\n| date=November 16, 1997| accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=ace2>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-01-16/entertainment/ca-20633_1_cableace-awards|title=HBO Takes Bulk of Prizes at the CableACE Awards \u2013 The Los Angeles Times| work=Los Angeles Times| date=January 16, 1995| accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> a [[Royal Television Society]] Award, two [[Gemini awards]], an [[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]], two Gold Dolphins from the [[Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards]],<ref name=golddolphin1>{{cite web|url= http://www.cannescorporate.com/en/winners2013.php|title= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards: Winners 2013\n | work= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=golddolphin2>{{cite web|url= http://www.cannescorporate.com/en/winners2014.php|title= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards: Winners 2014| work= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> a [[Jack R. Howard]] Award from the [[Scripps Howard]] Awards for In-Depth National and International Coverage,<ref name=scripps>{{cite web|url= http://www.shawards.org/PDF/Foundation-Release-3-14-14.pdf|title= Scripps Howard Awards Honor Nation\u2019s Best 2013 Journalism| work=Scripps Howard Foundation| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> the [[Norman Bethune]] Award from the [[Canadian Medical Association]] for Excellence in International Health Reporting<ref name=bethune>{{cite web|url= https://www.cma.ca/En/Lists/Medias/News_Release_Announcing_2014_Winners_Final.pdf|title= CMA Announces Recipients of 2014 Media Awards for Health Reporting| work=Canadian Medical Association| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> and, from the [[Overseas Press Club of America]], two [[Edward R. Murrow]] Awards and a [[Carl Spielvogel]] Award.\n\nIn 2017, he was awarded the [[Gordon Sinclair Award]],<ref name=\"academy.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.academy.ca/2017/gordon-sinclair-award-simcha-jacobovici/|title=Gordon Sinclair Award - Simcha Jacobovici - Academy.ca|date=17 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Canada's highest achievement in Broadcast Journalism, from the [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television]].\n\nAs an early advocate of airlifting [[Ethiopian Jews]] to Israel, he wrote an op-ed piece on the subject for ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]''<ref name=newyorkopinion1>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/10/02/opinion/ethiopia-s-black-jews-a-periled-community.html| title=Ethiopia\u2019s Black Jews, A Periled Community| last=Jacobovici| first=Simcha| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=October 2, 1981| accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=newyorkopinion2>{{cite news| last=Jacobovici| first=Simcha| title=Dying Ethiopian Jews| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=April 23, 1983}}</ref><ref name=newyorkopinion3>{{cite news| last=Jacobovici| first=Simcha| title=Ethiopian Jews Die, Israel Fiddles | work=[[The New York Times]]| date=September 15, 1984}}</ref><ref name=newyorktimesfalasha>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/10/opinion/l-holocaust-memories-and-a-refuge-for-the-jews-of-ethiopia-258504.html| title=Holocaust Memories and a Refuge for the Jews of Ethiopia - NYTimes.com| work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 10, 1984|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and made a documentary, ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'' (1983).<ref>{{cite book|title=Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews|date=1983|author= Jacobovici, Simcha |url=  https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/falasha_exile_of_the_black_jews/}}</ref>\n\nHis film on the [[Arab-Israeli conflict]], ''[[Deadly Currents]]'' (1991),<ref>{{cite book|title=Deadly Currents|author= Jacobovici, Simcha |date=1991|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deadly_currents-1996/}}</ref> won the [[Genie Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Feature Length Documentary|Best Documentary]]<ref>\"Naked Lunch top fare at Genies: 8 awards for surrealistic fantasy, but some films ill-served by presenters\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', November 23, 1992.</ref> and was the runner-up for the Peace Prize at the 1991 [[Berlin Film Festival]].<ref name=imdbcurrents>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0101681/awards?ref_=tt_awd| title=''Deadly Currents'' - Awards - IMDb| website=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJacobovici is presently (January 2020) in production as Series Director/Showrunner on a six-part series on the transatlantic slave trade, \"Enslaved: The Slave Trade As Told From the Ocean Floor\" ([[Epix/MGM]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], [[Fremantle Media]]). The series is hosted and co-executive produced by [[Samuel L Jackson]].\n\nJacobovici has coproduced three documentaries with [[James Cameron]] (''[[The Exodus Decoded]]'', ''[[The Lost Tomb of Jesus]]'' and ''[[Atlantis Rising]]'').\n\n==Controversies==\n\nSeveral of Jacobovici's films have sparked controversies. The 1994 film, ''The Plague Monkeys'' resulted in the closure of a level 4 lab in [[Toronto, Canada]]. ''[[James, Brother of Jesus]]'' highlighted an ossuary in the private collection of an Israeli antiquities collector, [[Oded Golan]]. Golan was accused of forging part of the inscription on a 2,000-year-old bone box/ossuary. Jacobovici and Hershel Shanks, the now-retired editor of [[Biblical Archaeology Review]] (BAR), stood by their story. After 7 years in an Israeli court, Golan was exonerated.<ref name=timesofisrael>{{cite web| url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/oded-golan-is-not-guilty-of-forgery-so-is-the-james-ossuary-for-real/| title=Oded Golan is not guilty of forgery| last=Friedman| first=Matti| work=[[The Times of Israel]]| date=March 14, 2012}}</ref> The claims made in ''The Lost Tomb of Jesus'' are still being debated by scholars.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Charlesworth  |first1=James |title=The Tomb of Jesus and His Family? Exploring Ancient Jewish Tombs Near Jerusalem's Walls |date=2013 | publisher=Eerdmans|location=Michigan |language= |isbn=9780802867452}}</ref>\n\n==Investigative archaeology==\nOver the past decades, Jacobovici has engaged in what he calls \"investigative archaeology\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/50434-jesus-family-tomb-geology.html|title=New Controversy Surrounds Alleged 'Jesus Family Tomb'|last=History|first=Tia Ghose 2015-04-09T16:32:00Z|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> His most controversial claim is the identification of a tomb in Jerusalem as that of [[Jesus of Nazareth]] and his family. The tomb was discovered in the [[Talpiot]] neighbourhood.<ref name=tombofjesus>{{cite web| url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1593893,00.html| title=Is This Jesus's Tomb? - TIME| last= Van Biema| first= David| work=[[TIME Magazine]]|date=February 26, 2007|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> In 2012, he investigated a Second Temple-era burial cave in [[Armon Hanatziv]] with a robotic arm that had a camera. He believes the cave may be the burial site of disciples of Jesus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/naked-archaeologist-finds-signs-jerusalem-cave-was-used-to-bury-jesus-disciples-1.415231|title='Naked Archaeologist' Finds Signs Jerusalem Cave Was Used to Bury Jesus' Disciples|first=Nir|last=Hasson|date=28 February 2012|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref>\n\nJacobovici hosted three seasons of ''[[The Naked Archaeologist]]'' on [[VisionTV]] in Canada<ref name=newswire>{{cite web| url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/703941/associated-producers-acclaimed-documentary-series-the-naked-archaeologist-returns-for-a-third-season-on-vision-tv-monday-march-22| title=VISIONTV - Associated Producers' acclaimed documentary series The Naked Archaeologist returns for a third season on Vision TV, Monday March 22|  work=CNW Group|date=March 10, 2010|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=apnaked>{{cite web| url=http://www.apltd.ca/films/display/16| title=The Naked Archaeologist (Season 3) - Associated Producers Ltd.|  work=Associated Producers Ltd.|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]] in the United States. In 2013, the series began to be broadcast on the Israel Broadcast Authority (IBA) Channel 1.\n\nJacobovici has written for ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[International Herald Tribune]]'', ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and other newspapers. He blogs on ''SimchaJTV'',<ref name=simchajtv>{{cite web| url=http://www.simchajtv.com/| title=SimchaJTV|  work=SimchaJTV|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Times of Israel]]''<ref name=timesblog>{{cite web| url=http://blogs.timesofisrael.com/author/simcha-jacobovici/| title=Simcha Jacobovici - Ops & Blogs - The Times of Israel|  work=[[The Times of Israel]]|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.<ref name=huffblog>{{cite web| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/simcha-jacobovici/| title=Simcha Jacobovici|  work=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc.|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref>   He occasionally writes for the [[The Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post]].\n \nHe has been interviewed on numerous television shows like ''[[Anderson Cooper 360]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'',''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', ''[[NBC Today Show]]'' and ''[[ABC Nightline]]''.\n\n\n\n== Books ==\n* {{Cite book |last1=Jacobovici  |first1=Simcha |first2=Charles |last2=Pellegrino |title=The Jesus Family Tomb: The Discovery, the Investigation, and the Evidence That Could Change History |date=March 2007 | publisher=HarperLuxe |location=New York |language= |isbn=0-06-125299-9}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Jacobovici |first1=Simcha |first2=James D. |last2=Tabor |title=The Jesus Discovery: The New Archaeological Find That Reveals the Birth of Christianity |date=January 2012 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |language= |isbn=1-4516-5040-X |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jesusdiscoveryne00tabo }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Jacobovici  |first1=Simcha |first2=Barrie |last2=Wilson |title=The Lost Gospel: Decoding the Ancient Text that Reveals Jesus' Marriage to Mary the Magdalene |date=November 2014 | publisher=Pegasus |location=New York |language= |isbn=1605986100}}\n\nJacobovici is also the co-author of two e-books; \"Michelangelo's Angels and Demons\"<ref name=ebook1>{{cite web| url=http://zoomerbooks.com/e-books/featured-books/biblical-conspiracies-michelangelos-angels-demons-companion-ebook/| title=Zoomer Books - ebooks Curated for Zoomers - Biblical Conspiracies: Michelangelo\u2019s Angels & Demons|  work=ZoomerMedia Ltd.|accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> and \"The James Revelation\",<ref name=ebook2>{{cite web| url=http://zoomerbooks.com/e-books/featured-books/biblical-conspiracies-james-revelation/| title=Zoomer Books - ebooks Curated for Zoomers - Biblical Conspiracies: The James Revelation|  work=ZoomerMedia Ltd.|accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> published by Zoomerbooks, as a companion to his television series \"Biblical Conspiracies\".\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Director===\n* ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'' (1983)\n* ''[[Deadly Currents]]'' (1991)\n* ''Expulsion and Memory: Descendants of the Hidden Jews'' (1996)\n* ''Hollywoodism: Jews, Movies & the American Dream'' (1997)\n* ''Quest for the Lost Tribes'' (2000)\n* ''The Struma'' (2001)\n* ''James, Brother of Jesus'' (2003)\n* ''[[The Exodus Decoded]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Naked Archaeologist]]'' (2006\u20132010)\n* ''Charging the Rhino'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Lost Tomb of Jesus]]'' (2007)\n* ''Secrets of Christianity/Decoding the Ancients'' (2010)\n* ''The Jesus Discovery/The Resurrection Tomb Mystery'' (2012)\n* ''Bride of God'' (Science Channel/VisionTV, 2014)\n* ''Atlantis Rising'' (National Geographic/Discovery, 2017)\n\n===Producer===\n* ''AIDS in Africa'' (1990)\n* ''The Plague Monkeys'' (1994)\n* ''Ebola: Inside an Outbreak/The Plague Fighters'' (1996)\n* ''The Selling of Innocents'' (1996)\n* ''Jesus in Russia: An American Holy War'' (1996)\n* ''Frozen Hearts'' (1999)\n* ''Pandemic: Case of the Killer Flu'' (1999)\n* ''Penn & Teller\u2019s Magic and Mystery Tour'' (2000)\n* ''Tell It Like It Is'' (2003/04)\n* ''Impact of Terror'' (2004)\n* ''Sex Slaves/The Real Sex Traffic'' (2005)\n* ''Yummy Mummy'' (2005)\n* ''Living in the Time of Jesus'' (2010)\n* ''Tales from the Organ Trade'' (2013)\n\n== Selected Awards ==\n* 2017 Gordon Sinclair Award from the Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television<ref name=\"academy.ca\"/>\n* 2015 Donald Brittain Award for Best Social/Political Documentary Program from the [[Canadian Screen Awards]] for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".<ref name=\"csa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.academy.ca/getmedia/89074442-5b8f-49f2-b666-1fb30d4f007b/2015-CSA-Feb24-Gala1Winners.aspx |title=CSA Gala 1 Winners |publisher= Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television. |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>\n* 2014 Edward R. Murrow Award from the Overseas Press Club of America for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".\n* 2014 Jack R. Howard Award for Television/Cable In-Depth National and International Coverage from the Scripps Howard Award for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".\n* 2014 Norman Bethune Award for Excellence in International Health Reporting from the Canadian Medical Association Media Awards for Health Reporting for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".\n* 2013 [[Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards]] Gold Dolphin in the category of \"Science & Knowledge\" for the documentary \"[[Resurrection Tomb Mystery]]\" (also released as The Jesus Discovery).<ref name=\"dolphinaward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cannescorporate.com/en/winners2013.php |title=Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards: Winners 2013|publisher=Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2013 Raven Award for Best Feature Documentary from the [[Southern Utah International Documentary Film Festival]] for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".<ref name=\"ravenaward\">{{cite web|url=http://docutah.com/2013-raven-award-winners |title=2013 WINNERS - DocUtah|publisher=Southern Utah International Documentary Film Festival |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2013 [[Banff World Media Festival]] Rockie Award in the category of \"Social & Humanitarian Documentaries\" for the documentary \"The Age of Anxiety\".<ref name=\"rockieaward\">{{cite web|url=http://banffmediafestival.com/content/984/2013+Rockies+Nominees |title=2013 Rockies Winners - BANFF WORLD MEDIA FESTIVAL, JUNE 8-11, 2014 |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2013 New York Festivals Gold World Medal in the category of \"Best Innovation\" for the documentary \"[[Resurrection Tomb Mystery]]\" (also released as The Jesus Discovery).<ref name=\"worldmedalaward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkfestivals.com/winners/2013/index.php |title=New York Festivals - 2013 World's Best Television & Films Winners |publisher= New York Festivals International Awards Group LLC. |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[CINE]] Golden Eagle Award in the \"History\" category for the documentary \"Beasts of the Bible\".<ref name=\"cineaward2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cine.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/2010-CINE-Winner-Directory.pdf |title=CINE Golden Eagle Awards - 2010 Winners |publisher= CINE |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[CINE]] Golden Eagle Award in the \"Science & Technology\" category for the documentary \"Science of the Soul\".<ref name=\"cineaward2\"/>\n* 2010 [[Religion Communicators Council]] Wilbur Award in the \"Television, Documentary\" category for the documentary \"Science of the Soul\".<ref name=\"wilbutaward1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.religioncommunicators.org/assets/documents/WilburAwardWinnersList2010.pdf |title=Wilbur Award Winners - 2010 |publisher= Religion Communicators Council |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2006 [[Edward Murrow Award (OPC)|Overseas Press Club Edward R. Murrow Award]] awarded to Ric Esther Bienstock, Felix Golubev, Simcha Jacobovici, David Fanning, and Ken Dornstein for 2005 documentary by Ric Esther Bienstock created in association with CBC, Channel 4 and Canal D, in the category of \"Best TV interpretation or documentary on international affairs\" for their [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS Frontline]] documentary \"[[Sex Slaves (film)|''Sex Slaves'']].\"<ref>http://www.opcofamerica.org/awards/awards-recipients?date_filter[value][year]=&field_award_recipient_value=Jacobovici&field_award_recip_affil_value=</ref>\n* 2006 UK [[Royal Television Society]] Award awarded to Ric Esther Bienstock, Felix Golubev, Simcha Jacobovici, David Fanning, and Ken Dornstein for 2005 documentary by Ric Esther Bienstock created in association with CBC, Channel 4 and Canal D, for their [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS Frontline]] documentary \"[[Sex Slaves (film)|''Sex Slaves'']].\"{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/awards |title=Awards &#124; Royal Television Society |publisher=Rts.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n* 2004 Overseas Press Club Carl Spielvogel Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://opcofamerica.org/awards/carl-spielvogel-award-2004|title=OPC  The Carl Spielvogel Award 2004|website=opcofamerica.org}}</ref> awarded to Tim Wolochatiuk, Simcha Jacobovici, Ric Esther Bienstock, Jennifer Hyde, and Sid Bedigfield for 2003 documentary by produced by Associated Producers for [[CNN]] and [[CNBC]] in the category of \"Best international reporting in the broadcast media showing a concern for the human condition\" for their documentary \"''[[CNN Presents]]: Impact of Terror''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0409/19/cp.00.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|website=transcripts.cnn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Award Name:&nbsp; 14 The Carl Spielvogel Award |url=http://opcofamerica.org/awards/carl-spielvogel-award-2004 |title=The Carl Spielvogel Award 2004 &#124; Overseas Press Club of America |publisher=Opcofamerica.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n* 1997 [[Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television]] [[Gemini Awards|Gemini Award]] in category of \"Best Science Documentary\" for the documentary \"''Ebola: Inside an Outbreak''\" (released internationally as Plague Fighters) for PBS\u2019 NOVA, Channel 4 and the CBC, written and directed by Ric Esther Bienstock<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/ric-bienstock|title=Ric Esther Bienstock - Associated Producers Ltd. - Associated Producers Ltd.|website=www.apltd.ca}}</ref> and produced by Simcha Jacobovici, Elliott Halpern, and Ric Esther Bienstock for Associated Producers, Ltd.<ref name=\"apltd.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apltd.ca/|title=Associated Producers Ltd.|website=www.apltd.ca}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}<ref name=\"apltd1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/ric-bienstock |title=Ric Esther Bienstock - Associated Producers Ltd. - Associated Producers Ltd |publisher=Apltd.ca |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n* 1997 [[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]] for Excellence in Broadcast Journalism for the documentary \"''Ebola: Inside an Outbreak''\" (released internationally as Plague Fighters) for PBS\u2019 NOVA, Channel 4 and the CBC, written and directed by [http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/ric-bienstock Ric Esther Bienstock] and produced by Simcha Jacobovici, Elliott Halpern, and Ric Esther Bienstock for Associated Producers, Ltd.<ref name=\"apltd.ca\"/><ref name=\"apltd1\" />\n* 1996 [[News & Documentary Emmy Award|News and Documentary Emmy Award]] in category of \"Outstanding Investigative Journalism\" for the documentary \"The Selling of Innocents\".\n* 1992 National Academy of Cable Programming [[CableACE Award]] for the documentary ''Deadly Currents'' produced in association with City TV.\n\n== Selected documentaries and television programs ==\n{{Merge from|Deadly Currents|date=July 2019}}\n=== ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'' ===\nIn the 1983 documentary ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'', Jacobovici tells the story of [[Beta Israel|Ethiopian Jews]], also called Falasha (strangers) and properly known as ''Beta Israel''. According to the documentary, the group was conquered by neighbouring tribes in the 17th century and suffered persecution.\n\nAfter the documentary, during the Israeli [[Operation Moses]] ({{lang-he-n|\u05de\u05b4\u05d1\u05b0\u05e6\u05b8\u05e2 \u05de\u05b9\u05e9\u05b6\u05c1\u05d4}}, ''Mivtza Moshe''), the Falasha were evacuated from [[Sudan]] during a famine in 1984 and airlifted to Israel.\n\n=== ''Expulsion & Memory: Descendants of the Hidden Jews'' ===\nIn the 1996 documentary, Jacobovici studies the [[Crypto-Judaism|Crypto-Jews]] of [[New Mexico]] and tiny populations of Jewish descendants in [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]], known as ''nuevos Cristianos'' (\"new Christians\"). He explores the Jewish ancestry of the New Mexican Hispanic families now living in New Mexico and finds that many of them have always been aware of their Jewish heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishfilm.org/Catalogue/films/expulsion.htm |title=Expulsion and Memory: Descendants of the Hidden Jews |publisher=Jewishfilm.org |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>\n\n===''The Struma''===\nIn the 2002 documentary, directed by Jacobovici, tells the story of {{MV|Struma}}, a small ship chartered to carry [[Jewish]] refugees from [[Axis powers|Axis]]-allied [[Romania]] to [[Mandatory Palestine]] during [[World War II]]. Ten people were let off the ship in [[Istanbul]], including a woman who had just had a miscarriage,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/24/world/middleeast/david-stoliar-survivor-of-world-war-ii-disaster-dies-at-91.html|title=David Stoliar, Survivor of World War II Disaster, Dies at 91|first=Robert D.|last=McFadden|date=1 November 2017|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref> and one man who was the representative of the [[Mobil Oil]] Company in Romania and was helped by Mobil's representative in [[Turkey]], [[Vehbi Koc]].{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} Koc asked the favour of the Istanbul Chief of Police, [[Sabri Caglayangil]], who later became a Minister of the Interior. On February 23, 1942, with her engine inoperable and her refugee passengers aboard, Turkish authorities towed ''Struma'' from Istanbul Harbour through the [[Bosphorus]] back to the [[Black Sea]],<ref name=Aroni>{{cite web |url= http://www.jewishgen.org/databases/holocaust/0140_Struma.html#P9 |last=Aroni |first=Samuel |title=Who Perished On The Struma And How Many? |year=2002\u20132007 |publisher=JewishGen.org}}</ref> where they set her adrift without food, water or fuel. Within hours, on the morning of February 24, she was [[struma disaster|torpedoed and sunk]] by the {{Ship|Soviet submarine|Shch-213||2|up=yes}}, killing at least 768 men, women and children and possibly as many as 791, 785 of whom were Jews.<ref name=Aroni/>\n\nThe documentary won the Audience Award at the [[Portland International Film Festival]] for best documentary.\n\n=== ''Quest for the Lost Tribes'' ===\nIn the 2003 wide-ranging documentary, Jacobovici goes on a worldwide search for the [[Ten Lost Tribes of Israel]] and states that there are actually only nine since the remnant of the [[tribe of Dan]] was confirmed{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} to be the Beta Israel of Ethiopia. Travelling from western [[Europe]] to [[China]] and [[India]], Jacobovici finds tantalizing evidence that the \"lost tribes\" are, like the tribe of Dan, not really lost. The tribe of Dan is the only original tribe of Israel not to be included in the [[Book of Revelation]]'s list of tribes that are sealed. No mention is made of why it is excluded.\n\n=== ''Impact of Terror'' ===\nThe 2004 documentary, produced by Jacobovici and directed by [[Tim Wolochatiuk]], is about Israeli victims of terrorism struggling to cope in the aftermath of the August 2001 [[Sbarro restaurant suicide bombing]] in [[Jerusalem]].\n\n=== ''[[The Exodus Decoded]]'' ===\nThe 2006 [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] documentary was created by Jacobovici and the producer/director [[James Cameron]]. It explores evidence for the [[biblical]] account of [[the Exodus]]. Its claims and methods were widely criticized by Biblical scholars and by mainstream scientists.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblearchaeology.org/post/2006/09/debunking-the-exodus-decoded.aspx|title=Debunking \"The Exodus Decoded\"|first=Bryant G. Wood|last=PhD|website=www.biblearchaeology.org}}</ref><ref>[http://www.heardworld.com/higgaion/?page_id=119 Higgaion \u00bb Exodus Decoded<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodusbeware.html |title=Biblical Archaeology Society |accessdate=2011-08-15 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502122212/http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodusbeware.html |archivedate=May 2, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodus.html |title=Biblical Archaeology Society |accessdate=2011-03-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070528054314/http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodus.html |archivedate=May 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nJacobovici suggests that the Exodus took place around 1500 BC, during the reign of Pharaoh [[Ahmose I]], and that it coincided with the [[Minoan eruption]]. In the documentary, the biblical [[plagues of Egypt]] are explained as having resulted from that eruption and a related [[limnic eruption]] in the [[Nile Delta]]. While much of Jacobovici's archaeological evidence for the Exodus comes from Egypt, some comes from [[Mycenae]] on Mainland Greece, such as a gold ornament that somewhat resembles the [[Ark of the Covenant]].\n\nThe documentary makes extensive use of computer animation and visual effects made by Gravity Visual Effects, Inc. It runs for 90 min and was first aired in [[Canada]] on April 16 ([[Easter Day]]), 2006 (''[[Discovery Channel (Canada)|Discovery Channel Canada]]''). It was shown in the [[United States]] on August 20, 2006 (''[[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel US]]''), [[United Kingdom|UK]] on December 23, 2006 (''[[Discovery Channel (UK and Ireland)|Discovery Channel UK]]'') and [[Spain]] on December 25, 2006 ([[Cuatro (channel)|Cuatro]]).\n\n=== ''[[The Lost Tomb of Jesus]]'' ===\nThe documentary was co-produced and first broadcast on the [[Discovery Channel]] and [[Vision TV]] in Canada on March 4, 2007, covering the discovery of the [[Talpiot Tomb]]. It was directed by Jacobovici and produced by Felix Golubev and [[Ric Esther Bienstock]], and [[James Cameron]] served as executive producer. It was released in conjunction with a book on the same subject, ''[[The Jesus Family Tomb]]'', issued in late February 2007 and co-authored by Jacobovici and [[Charles R. Pellegrino]]. The documentary and book has claims that are disputed by some [[archaeologists]] and [[theologians]] fields as well as some linguistic and biblical scholars.\n\n=== ''[[The Naked Archaeologist]]'' ===\nThe television show was produced for [[VisionTV]] in Canada and [[History International]] in the US and was hosted and prepared by Jacobovici and [[Avri Gilad]]. The show ultimately reviewed biblical stories and then tried to find proof for them by exploring the [[Holy Land]] looking for archaeological evidence, making personal inferences and deductions and interviewing scholars and experts. After its original run on [[VisionTV]], it was picked up in the U.S. by [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]] and its sister network, [[History International]].\n\nThe episode \"A Nabatean by Any Other Name\" won the Special Jury Prize at the 8th International Archaeological Film Festival in [[Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kineon.be/Palmares-2009.html|title=List of Award Winners, 2009 Festival International du Film Archaeologique de Bruxelles|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Finding Atlantis'' ===\nJacobovici was involved as executive producer<ref>[http://www.apltd.ca/films/display/57 Finding Atlantis - Apltd.]</ref> in the production of a documentary that was shown in March 2010 on the [[National Geographic Channel]]. He claimed that [[Atlantis]] had been found in Spain, and he said that evidence found by [[University of Hartford]] Professor Richard Freund included the unearthed emblem of Atlantis and that \"[[Tarshish]] is Atlantis itself\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hartman|first=Ben|title=The deepest Jewish encampment?|url=http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=212935|accessdate=22 March 2011|newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Atlantis Rising'' ===\nIn 2016, Jacobovici directed a documentary on Atlantis for National Geographic Channel; its executive producer was James Cameron. Shot in several places in the [[Mediterranean]] ([[Greece]], [[Sardinia]], [[Malta]], [[Santorini]]) such as in Spain ([[C\u00e1diz]], [[Huelva]], [[Sevilla]], [[Ja\u00e9n, Spain|Ja\u00e9n]], [[Ciudad Real]], [[Badajoz]] and other undersea places in the [[Gulf of C\u00e1diz]]) and the [[Azores]]. It premiered on January 29, 2017 on National Geographic Channel (US)<ref>https://www.natgeotvpressroom.com/articles/show/587fc611fb8ca7dd374f3bc0</ref> and at National Geographic Spain as \"El Resurgir de la Atl\u00e1ntida\" on March 5, 2017.<ref>[https://twitter.com/NatGeoEspana/status/838249222675681280 National Geographic Espa\u00f1a: James Cameron es el productor de 'El Resurgir de la Atlantida', estreno esta tarde en NatGeo]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.apltd.ca/ Associated Producers Ltd.]\n* [http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/simcha-jacobovici Associated Producers Ltd. - Simcha Jacobovici]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0414302|name=Simcha Jacobovici}}\n* [http://www.jesusfamilytomb.com/ Official Site for ''The Lost Tomb of Jesus'']\n* [http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/34311/canadian-director-honors-father-murdered-romanian-jews/ Simcha Jacobovici honors his father]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/thehour/video.php?id=1437 Simcha Jacobovici Interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobovici, Simcha}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Israeli descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Israeli Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:Pseudoarchaeologists]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistorians]]\n[[Category:People from Petah Tikva]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Directors of Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners for Best Documentary Film]]\n[[Category:Historical theories and materials on the Exodus]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|reason=general standards|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        =Simcha Jacobovici\n|image       =SimchaJacobovici-002.JPG\n|alt         =\n|caption     =\n|birth_date  ={{Birth date and age|1953|04|04}}\n|birth_place =[[Petah Tikva]], [[Israel]]\n|death_date  =<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n|death_place =\n|nationality =[[Canadian nationality law|Canadian]] / [[Israeli nationality law|Israeli]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   =\n|education   = [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[McGill University]]<br>[[Master of Arts|M.A.]], [[University of Toronto]]\n|occupation  =Film director, producer, journalist, writer\n}}\n'''Simcha Jacobovici''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u026a|m|x|\u0259|_|j|\u0259|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|b|o\u028a-|v|\u026a|t\u0283}}; born April 4, 1953 in [[Petah Tikva]], [[Israel]]) is an [[Israeli Canadians|Israeli-Canadian]] multi award-winning film director, producer, freelance journalist, and ''New York Times'' bestselling author.\n\n==Biography==\nSimcha Jacobovici's parents were from [[Ia\u0219i]], [[Romania]].<ref>[http://www.libertatea.ro/ultima-ora/sicriul-lui-iisus-opera-unui-roman-180286 'Sicriul lui Iisus', opera unui roman], 27 February 2007, ''Libertatea'', Retrieved 19 February 2017</ref> He was born April 4, 1953, in Petach Tikvah, Israel. In 1962, the family relocated to Canada.\n\nHe earned a B.A. in Philosophy and Political Science (with honors) from [[McGill University]] and an M.A. in International Relations from the [[University of Toronto]]. {{asof|2015}} he was an [[Adjunct Professor]] of Religious Studies at [[Huntington University (Canada)|Huntington University]],<ref name=huntington>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114853/http://www.huntingtonu.ca/faculty/simcha-jacobovici| title=Simcha Jacobovici - Huntington University| work=Huntington University| accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref> in Greater Sudbury, Ontario. He is married and the father of five children.\n\n==Film career==\n\nJacobovici is a three time [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] winner for Outstanding Investigative Journalism<ref name=emmyonline>{{cite web| url=http://www.emmyonline.org/mediacenter/news_28th_nominees_data_list.html| title=The Emmy Awards - 27th Annual News & Documentary Emmy Awards| work=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences| accessdate=November 4, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220155142/http://www.emmyonline.org/mediacenter/news_28th_nominees_data_list.html| archivedate=February 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=playbackonline>{{cite web| url=http://playbackonline.ca/1997/09/22/19286-19970922/| title=The importance of winning Emmy(s)| last=Maddever| first=Mary| work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]| date=November 22, 1997| accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and a ''[[New York Times]]'' bestselling author.<ref name=newyorktimeslist>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/18/books/bestseller/0318besthardnonfiction.html?_r=0| title=Hardcover Nonfiction - The New York Times| work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 18, 2007| accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> l His filmmaking awards also include a certificate of Special Merit from the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], a Gold Medal from the International Documentary Festival of [[Nyon]], two US [[CableACE Award]]s,<ref name=ace1>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1997/tv/news/cableace-awards-111661098/|title=CableAce Awards - Variety| work=Variety Media, LLC\n| date=November 16, 1997| accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=ace2>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-01-16/entertainment/ca-20633_1_cableace-awards|title=HBO Takes Bulk of Prizes at the CableACE Awards \u2013 The Los Angeles Times| work=Los Angeles Times| date=January 16, 1995| accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> a [[Royal Television Society]] Award, two [[Gemini awards]], an [[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]], two Gold Dolphins from the [[Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards]],<ref name=golddolphin1>{{cite web|url= http://www.cannescorporate.com/en/winners2013.php|title= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards: Winners 2013\n | work= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=golddolphin2>{{cite web|url= http://www.cannescorporate.com/en/winners2014.php|title= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards: Winners 2014| work= Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> a [[Jack R. Howard]] Award from the [[Scripps Howard]] Awards for In-Depth National and International Coverage,<ref name=scripps>{{cite web|url= http://www.shawards.org/PDF/Foundation-Release-3-14-14.pdf|title= Scripps Howard Awards Honor Nation\u2019s Best 2013 Journalism| work=Scripps Howard Foundation| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> the [[Norman Bethune]] Award from the [[Canadian Medical Association]] for Excellence in International Health Reporting<ref name=bethune>{{cite web|url= https://www.cma.ca/En/Lists/Medias/News_Release_Announcing_2014_Winners_Final.pdf|title= CMA Announces Recipients of 2014 Media Awards for Health Reporting| work=Canadian Medical Association| accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> and, from the [[Overseas Press Club of America]], two [[Edward R. Murrow]] Awards and a [[Carl Spielvogel]] Award.\n\nIn 2017, he was awarded the [[Gordon Sinclair Award]],<ref name=\"academy.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.academy.ca/2017/gordon-sinclair-award-simcha-jacobovici/|title=Gordon Sinclair Award - Simcha Jacobovici - Academy.ca|date=17 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Canada's highest achievement in Broadcast Journalism, from the [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television]].\n\nAs an early advocate of airlifting [[Ethiopian Jews]] to Israel, he wrote an op-ed piece on the subject for ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]''<ref name=newyorkopinion1>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/10/02/opinion/ethiopia-s-black-jews-a-periled-community.html| title=Ethiopia\u2019s Black Jews, A Periled Community| last=Jacobovici| first=Simcha| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=October 2, 1981| accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=newyorkopinion2>{{cite news| last=Jacobovici| first=Simcha| title=Dying Ethiopian Jews| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=April 23, 1983}}</ref><ref name=newyorkopinion3>{{cite news| last=Jacobovici| first=Simcha| title=Ethiopian Jews Die, Israel Fiddles | work=[[The New York Times]]| date=September 15, 1984}}</ref><ref name=newyorktimesfalasha>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/10/opinion/l-holocaust-memories-and-a-refuge-for-the-jews-of-ethiopia-258504.html| title=Holocaust Memories and a Refuge for the Jews of Ethiopia - NYTimes.com| work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 10, 1984|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and made a documentary, ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'' (1983).<ref>{{cite book|title=Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews|date=1983|author= Jacobovici, Simcha |url=  https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/falasha_exile_of_the_black_jews/}}</ref>\n\nHis film on the [[Arab-Israeli conflict]], ''[[Deadly Currents]]'' (1991),<ref>{{cite book|title=Deadly Currents|author= Jacobovici, Simcha |date=1991|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deadly_currents-1996/}}</ref> won the [[Genie Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Feature Length Documentary|Best Documentary]]<ref>\"Naked Lunch top fare at Genies: 8 awards for surrealistic fantasy, but some films ill-served by presenters\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', November 23, 1992.</ref> and was the runner-up for the Peace Prize at the 1991 [[Berlin Film Festival]].<ref name=imdbcurrents>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0101681/awards?ref_=tt_awd| title=''Deadly Currents'' - Awards - IMDb| website=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJacobovici is presently (January 2020) in production as Series Director/Showrunner on a six-part series on the transatlantic slave trade, \"Enslaved: The Slave Trade As Told From the Ocean Floor\" ([[Epix/MGM]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], [[Fremantle Media]]). The series is hosted and co-executive produced by [[Samuel L Jackson]].\n\nJacobovici has coproduced three documentaries with [[James Cameron]] (''[[The Exodus Decoded]]'', ''[[The Lost Tomb of Jesus]]'' and ''[[Atlantis Rising]]'').\n\n==Controversies==\n\nSeveral of Jacobovici's films have sparked controversies. The 1994 film, ''The Plague Monkeys'' resulted in the closure of a level 4 lab in [[Toronto, Canada]]. ''[[James, Brother of Jesus]]'' highlighted an ossuary in the private collection of an Israeli antiquities collector, [[Oded Golan]]. Golan was accused of forging part of the inscription on a 2,000-year-old bone box/ossuary. Jacobovici and Hershel Shanks, the now-retired editor of [[Biblical Archaeology Review]] (BAR), stood by their story. After 7 years in an Israeli court, Golan was exonerated<ref name=timesofisrael>{{cite web| url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/oded-golan-is-not-guilty-of-forgery-so-is-the-james-ossuary-for-real/| title=Oded Golan is not guilty of forgery| last=Friedman| first=Matti| work=[[The Times of Israel]]| date=March 14, 2012}}</ref>. The claims made in ''The Lost Tomb of Jesus'' are still being debated by scholars.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Charlesworth  |first1=James |title=The Tomb of Jesus and His Family? Exploring Ancient Jewish Tombs Near Jerusalem's Walls |date=2013 | publisher=Eerdmans|location=Michigan |language= |isbn=9780802867452}}</ref>\n\n==Investigative archaeology==\nOver the past decades, Jacobovici has engaged in what he calls \"investigative archaeology\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/50434-jesus-family-tomb-geology.html|title=New Controversy Surrounds Alleged 'Jesus Family Tomb'|last=History|first=Tia Ghose 2015-04-09T16:32:00Z|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> His most controversial claim is the identification of a tomb in Jerusalem as that of [[Jesus of Nazareth]] and his family. The tomb was discovered in the [[Talpiot]] neighbourhood.<ref name=tombofjesus>{{cite web| url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1593893,00.html| title=Is This Jesus's Tomb? - TIME| last= Van Biema| first= David| work=[[TIME Magazine]]|date=February 26, 2007|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> In 2012, he investigated a Second Temple-era burial cave in [[Armon Hanatziv]] with a robotic arm that had a camera. He believes the cave may be the burial site of disciples of Jesus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/naked-archaeologist-finds-signs-jerusalem-cave-was-used-to-bury-jesus-disciples-1.415231|title='Naked Archaeologist' Finds Signs Jerusalem Cave Was Used to Bury Jesus' Disciples|first=Nir|last=Hasson|date=28 February 2012|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref>\n\nJacobovici hosted three seasons of ''[[The Naked Archaeologist]]'' on [[VisionTV]] in Canada<ref name=newswire>{{cite web| url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/703941/associated-producers-acclaimed-documentary-series-the-naked-archaeologist-returns-for-a-third-season-on-vision-tv-monday-march-22| title=VISIONTV - Associated Producers' acclaimed documentary series The Naked Archaeologist returns for a third season on Vision TV, Monday March 22|  work=CNW Group|date=March 10, 2010|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=apnaked>{{cite web| url=http://www.apltd.ca/films/display/16| title=The Naked Archaeologist (Season 3) - Associated Producers Ltd.|  work=Associated Producers Ltd.|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]] in the United States. In 2013, the series began to be broadcast on the Israel Broadcast Authority (IBA) Channel 1.\n\nJacobovici has written for ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[International Herald Tribune]]'', ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and other newspapers. He blogs on ''SimchaJTV'',<ref name=simchajtv>{{cite web| url=http://www.simchajtv.com/| title=SimchaJTV|  work=SimchaJTV|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Times of Israel]]''<ref name=timesblog>{{cite web| url=http://blogs.timesofisrael.com/author/simcha-jacobovici/| title=Simcha Jacobovici - Ops & Blogs - The Times of Israel|  work=[[The Times of Israel]]|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> and ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.<ref name=huffblog>{{cite web| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/simcha-jacobovici/| title=Simcha Jacobovici|  work=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc.|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref>   He occasionally writes for the [[The Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post]].\n \nHe has been interviewed on numerous television shows like ''[[Anderson Cooper 360]]'', ''[[Larry King Live]]'',''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', ''[[NBC Today Show]]'' and ''[[ABC Nightline]]''.\n\n\n\n== Books ==\n* {{Cite book |last1=Jacobovici  |first1=Simcha |first2=Charles |last2=Pellegrino |title=The Jesus Family Tomb: The Discovery, the Investigation, and the Evidence That Could Change History |date=March 2007 | publisher=HarperLuxe |location=New York |language= |isbn=0-06-125299-9}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Jacobovici |first1=Simcha |first2=James D. |last2=Tabor |title=The Jesus Discovery: The New Archaeological Find That Reveals the Birth of Christianity |date=January 2012 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |language= |isbn=1-4516-5040-X |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jesusdiscoveryne00tabo }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Jacobovici  |first1=Simcha |first2=Barrie |last2=Wilson |title=The Lost Gospel: Decoding the Ancient Text that Reveals Jesus' Marriage to Mary the Magdalene |date=November 2014 | publisher=Pegasus |location=New York |language= |isbn=1605986100}}\n\nJacobovici is also the co-author of two e-books; \"Michelangelo's Angels and Demons\"<ref name=ebook1>{{cite web| url=http://zoomerbooks.com/e-books/featured-books/biblical-conspiracies-michelangelos-angels-demons-companion-ebook/| title=Zoomer Books - ebooks Curated for Zoomers - Biblical Conspiracies: Michelangelo\u2019s Angels & Demons|  work=ZoomerMedia Ltd.|accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> and \"The James Revelation\",<ref name=ebook2>{{cite web| url=http://zoomerbooks.com/e-books/featured-books/biblical-conspiracies-james-revelation/| title=Zoomer Books - ebooks Curated for Zoomers - Biblical Conspiracies: The James Revelation|  work=ZoomerMedia Ltd.|accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref> published by Zoomerbooks, as a companion to his television series \"Biblical Conspiracies\".\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Director===\n* ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'' (1983)\n* ''[[Deadly Currents]]'' (1991)\n* ''Expulsion and Memory: Descendants of the Hidden Jews'' (1996)\n* ''Hollywoodism: Jews, Movies & the American Dream'' (1997)\n* ''Quest for the Lost Tribes'' (2000)\n* ''The Struma'' (2001)\n* ''James, Brother of Jesus'' (2003)\n* ''[[The Exodus Decoded]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Naked Archaeologist]]'' (2006\u20132010)\n* ''Charging the Rhino'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Lost Tomb of Jesus]]'' (2007)\n* ''Secrets of Christianity/Decoding the Ancients'' (2010)\n* ''The Jesus Discovery/The Resurrection Tomb Mystery'' (2012)\n* ''Bride of God'' (Science Channel/VisionTV, 2014)\n* ''Atlantis Rising'' (National Geographic/Discovery, 2017)\n\n===Producer===\n* ''AIDS in Africa'' (1990)\n* ''The Plague Monkeys'' (1994)\n* ''Ebola: Inside an Outbreak/The Plague Fighters'' (1996)\n* ''The Selling of Innocents'' (1996)\n* ''Jesus in Russia: An American Holy War'' (1996)\n* ''Frozen Hearts'' (1999)\n* ''Pandemic: Case of the Killer Flu'' (1999)\n* ''Penn & Teller\u2019s Magic and Mystery Tour'' (2000)\n* ''Tell It Like It Is'' (2003/04)\n* ''Impact of Terror'' (2004)\n* ''Sex Slaves/The Real Sex Traffic'' (2005)\n* ''Yummy Mummy'' (2005)\n* ''Living in the Time of Jesus'' (2010)\n* ''Tales from the Organ Trade'' (2013)\n\n== Selected Awards ==\n* 2017 Gordon Sinclair Award from the Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television<ref name=\"academy.ca\"/>\n* 2015 Donald Brittain Award for Best Social/Political Documentary Program from the [[Canadian Screen Awards]] for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".<ref name=\"csa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.academy.ca/getmedia/89074442-5b8f-49f2-b666-1fb30d4f007b/2015-CSA-Feb24-Gala1Winners.aspx |title=CSA Gala 1 Winners |publisher= Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television. |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>\n* 2014 Edward R. Murrow Award from the Overseas Press Club of America for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".\n* 2014 Jack R. Howard Award for Television/Cable In-Depth National and International Coverage from the Scripps Howard Award for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".\n* 2014 Norman Bethune Award for Excellence in International Health Reporting from the Canadian Medical Association Media Awards for Health Reporting for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".\n* 2013 [[Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards]] Gold Dolphin in the category of \"Science & Knowledge\" for the documentary \"[[Resurrection Tomb Mystery]]\" (also released as The Jesus Discovery).<ref name=\"dolphinaward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cannescorporate.com/en/winners2013.php |title=Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards: Winners 2013|publisher=Cannes Corporate Media & TV Awards |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2013 Raven Award for Best Feature Documentary from the [[Southern Utah International Documentary Film Festival]] for the documentary \"[[Tales from the Organ Trade]]\".<ref name=\"ravenaward\">{{cite web|url=http://docutah.com/2013-raven-award-winners |title=2013 WINNERS - DocUtah|publisher=Southern Utah International Documentary Film Festival |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2013 [[Banff World Media Festival]] Rockie Award in the category of \"Social & Humanitarian Documentaries\" for the documentary \"The Age of Anxiety\".<ref name=\"rockieaward\">{{cite web|url=http://banffmediafestival.com/content/984/2013+Rockies+Nominees |title=2013 Rockies Winners - BANFF WORLD MEDIA FESTIVAL, JUNE 8-11, 2014 |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2013 New York Festivals Gold World Medal in the category of \"Best Innovation\" for the documentary \"[[Resurrection Tomb Mystery]]\" (also released as The Jesus Discovery).<ref name=\"worldmedalaward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkfestivals.com/winners/2013/index.php |title=New York Festivals - 2013 World's Best Television & Films Winners |publisher= New York Festivals International Awards Group LLC. |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[CINE]] Golden Eagle Award in the \"History\" category for the documentary \"Beasts of the Bible\".<ref name=\"cineaward2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cine.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/2010-CINE-Winner-Directory.pdf |title=CINE Golden Eagle Awards - 2010 Winners |publisher= CINE |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[CINE]] Golden Eagle Award in the \"Science & Technology\" category for the documentary \"Science of the Soul\".<ref name=\"cineaward2\"/>\n* 2010 [[Religion Communicators Council]] Wilbur Award in the \"Television, Documentary\" category for the documentary \"Science of the Soul\".<ref name=\"wilbutaward1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.religioncommunicators.org/assets/documents/WilburAwardWinnersList2010.pdf |title=Wilbur Award Winners - 2010 |publisher= Religion Communicators Council |date= |accessdate=2014-01-06}}</ref>\n* 2006 [[Edward Murrow Award (OPC)|Overseas Press Club Edward R. Murrow Award]] awarded to Ric Esther Bienstock, Felix Golubev, Simcha Jacobovici, David Fanning, and Ken Dornstein for 2005 documentary by Ric Esther Bienstock created in association with CBC, Channel 4 and Canal D, in the category of \"Best TV interpretation or documentary on international affairs\" for their [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS Frontline]] documentary \"[[Sex Slaves (film)|''Sex Slaves'']].\"<ref>http://www.opcofamerica.org/awards/awards-recipients?date_filter[value][year]=&field_award_recipient_value=Jacobovici&field_award_recip_affil_value=</ref>\n* 2006 UK [[Royal Television Society]] Award awarded to Ric Esther Bienstock, Felix Golubev, Simcha Jacobovici, David Fanning, and Ken Dornstein for 2005 documentary by Ric Esther Bienstock created in association with CBC, Channel 4 and Canal D, for their [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS Frontline]] documentary \"[[Sex Slaves (film)|''Sex Slaves'']].\"{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/awards |title=Awards &#124; Royal Television Society |publisher=Rts.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n* 2004 Overseas Press Club Carl Spielvogel Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://opcofamerica.org/awards/carl-spielvogel-award-2004|title=OPC  The Carl Spielvogel Award 2004|website=opcofamerica.org}}</ref> awarded to Tim Wolochatiuk, Simcha Jacobovici, Ric Esther Bienstock, Jennifer Hyde, and Sid Bedigfield for 2003 documentary by produced by Associated Producers for [[CNN]] and [[CNBC]] in the category of \"Best international reporting in the broadcast media showing a concern for the human condition\" for their documentary \"''[[CNN Presents]]: Impact of Terror''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0409/19/cp.00.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|website=transcripts.cnn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Award Name:&nbsp; 14 The Carl Spielvogel Award |url=http://opcofamerica.org/awards/carl-spielvogel-award-2004 |title=The Carl Spielvogel Award 2004 &#124; Overseas Press Club of America |publisher=Opcofamerica.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n* 1997 [[Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television]] [[Gemini Awards|Gemini Award]] in category of \"Best Science Documentary\" for the documentary \"''Ebola: Inside an Outbreak''\" (released internationally as Plague Fighters) for PBS\u2019 NOVA, Channel 4 and the CBC, written and directed by Ric Esther Bienstock<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/ric-bienstock|title=Ric Esther Bienstock - Associated Producers Ltd. - Associated Producers Ltd.|website=www.apltd.ca}}</ref> and produced by Simcha Jacobovici, Elliott Halpern, and Ric Esther Bienstock for Associated Producers, Ltd.<ref name=\"apltd.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apltd.ca/|title=Associated Producers Ltd.|website=www.apltd.ca}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}<ref name=\"apltd1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/ric-bienstock |title=Ric Esther Bienstock - Associated Producers Ltd. - Associated Producers Ltd |publisher=Apltd.ca |date= |accessdate=2012-08-26}}</ref>\n* 1997 [[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]] for Excellence in Broadcast Journalism for the documentary \"''Ebola: Inside an Outbreak''\" (released internationally as Plague Fighters) for PBS\u2019 NOVA, Channel 4 and the CBC, written and directed by [http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/ric-bienstock Ric Esther Bienstock] and produced by Simcha Jacobovici, Elliott Halpern, and Ric Esther Bienstock for Associated Producers, Ltd.<ref name=\"apltd.ca\"/><ref name=\"apltd1\" />\n* 1996 [[News & Documentary Emmy Award|News and Documentary Emmy Award]] in category of \"Outstanding Investigative Journalism\" for the documentary \"The Selling of Innocents\".\n* 1992 National Academy of Cable Programming [[CableACE Award]] for the documentary ''Deadly Currents'' produced in association with City TV.\n\n== Selected documentaries and television programs ==\n{{Merge from|Deadly Currents|date=July 2019}}\n=== ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'' ===\nIn the 1983 documentary ''Falasha: Exile of the Black Jews'', Jacobovici tells the story of [[Beta Israel|Ethiopian Jews]], also called Falasha (strangers) and properly known as ''Beta Israel''. According to the documentary, the group was conquered by neighbouring tribes in the 17th century and suffered persecution.\n\nAfter the documentary, during the Israeli [[Operation Moses]] ({{lang-he-n|\u05de\u05b4\u05d1\u05b0\u05e6\u05b8\u05e2 \u05de\u05b9\u05e9\u05b6\u05c1\u05d4}}, ''Mivtza Moshe''), the Falasha were evacuated from [[Sudan]] during a famine in 1984 and airlifted to Israel.\n\n=== ''Expulsion & Memory: Descendants of the Hidden Jews'' ===\nIn the 1996 documentary, Jacobovici studies the [[Crypto-Judaism|Crypto-Jews]] of [[New Mexico]] and tiny populations of Jewish descendants in [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]], known as ''nuevos Cristianos'' (\"new Christians\"). He explores the Jewish ancestry of the New Mexican Hispanic families now living in New Mexico and finds that many of them have always been aware of their Jewish heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishfilm.org/Catalogue/films/expulsion.htm |title=Expulsion and Memory: Descendants of the Hidden Jews |publisher=Jewishfilm.org |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>\n\n===''The Struma''===\nIn the 2002 documentary, directed by Jacobovici, tells the story of {{MV|Struma}}, a small ship chartered to carry [[Jewish]] refugees from [[Axis powers|Axis]]-allied [[Romania]] to [[Mandatory Palestine]] during [[World War II]]. Ten people were let off the ship in [[Istanbul]], including a woman who had just had a miscarriage,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/24/world/middleeast/david-stoliar-survivor-of-world-war-ii-disaster-dies-at-91.html|title=David Stoliar, Survivor of World War II Disaster, Dies at 91|first=Robert D.|last=McFadden|date=1 November 2017|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref> and one man who was the representative of the [[Mobil Oil]] Company in Romania and was helped by Mobil's representative in [[Turkey]], [[Vehbi Koc]].{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} Koc asked the favour of the Istanbul Chief of Police, [[Sabri Caglayangil]], who later became a Minister of the Interior. On February 23, 1942, with her engine inoperable and her refugee passengers aboard, Turkish authorities towed ''Struma'' from Istanbul Harbour through the [[Bosphorus]] back to the [[Black Sea]],<ref name=Aroni>{{cite web |url= http://www.jewishgen.org/databases/holocaust/0140_Struma.html#P9 |last=Aroni |first=Samuel |title=Who Perished On The Struma And How Many? |year=2002\u20132007 |publisher=JewishGen.org}}</ref> where they set her adrift without food, water or fuel. Within hours, on the morning of February 24, she was [[struma disaster|torpedoed and sunk]] by the {{Ship|Soviet submarine|Shch-213||2|up=yes}}, killing at least 768 men, women and children and possibly as many as 791, 785 of whom were Jews.<ref name=Aroni/>\n\nThe documentary won the Audience Award at the [[Portland International Film Festival]] for best documentary.\n\n=== ''Quest for the Lost Tribes'' ===\nIn the 2003 wide-ranging documentary, Jacobovici goes on a worldwide search for the [[Ten Lost Tribes of Israel]] and states that there are actually only nine since the remnant of the [[tribe of Dan]] was confirmed{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} to be the Beta Israel of Ethiopia. Travelling from western [[Europe]] to [[China]] and [[India]], Jacobovici finds tantalizing evidence that the \"lost tribes\" are, like the tribe of Dan, not really lost. The tribe of Dan is the only original tribe of Israel not to be included in the [[Book of Revelation]]'s list of tribes that are sealed. No mention is made of why it is excluded.\n\n=== ''Impact of Terror'' ===\nThe 2004 documentary, produced by Jacobovici and directed by [[Tim Wolochatiuk]], is about Israeli victims of terrorism struggling to cope in the aftermath of the August 2001 [[Sbarro restaurant suicide bombing]] in [[Jerusalem]].\n\n=== ''[[The Exodus Decoded]]'' ===\nThe 2006 [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] documentary was created by Jacobovici and the producer/director [[James Cameron]]. It explores evidence for the [[biblical]] account of [[the Exodus]]. Its claims and methods were widely criticized by Biblical scholars and by mainstream scientists.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblearchaeology.org/post/2006/09/debunking-the-exodus-decoded.aspx|title=Debunking \"The Exodus Decoded\"|first=Bryant G. Wood|last=PhD|website=www.biblearchaeology.org}}</ref><ref>[http://www.heardworld.com/higgaion/?page_id=119 Higgaion \u00bb Exodus Decoded<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodusbeware.html |title=Biblical Archaeology Society |accessdate=2011-08-15 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502122212/http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodusbeware.html |archivedate=May 2, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodus.html |title=Biblical Archaeology Society |accessdate=2011-03-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070528054314/http://www.bib-arch.org/bswbOOexodus.html |archivedate=May 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nJacobovici suggests that the Exodus took place around 1500 BC, during the reign of Pharaoh [[Ahmose I]], and that it coincided with the [[Minoan eruption]]. In the documentary, the biblical [[plagues of Egypt]] are explained as having resulted from that eruption and a related [[limnic eruption]] in the [[Nile Delta]]. While much of Jacobovici's archaeological evidence for the Exodus comes from Egypt, some comes from [[Mycenae]] on Mainland Greece, such as a gold ornament that somewhat resembles the [[Ark of the Covenant]].\n\nThe documentary makes extensive use of computer animation and visual effects made by Gravity Visual Effects, Inc. It runs for 90 min and was first aired in [[Canada]] on April 16 ([[Easter Day]]), 2006 (''[[Discovery Channel (Canada)|Discovery Channel Canada]]''). It was shown in the [[United States]] on August 20, 2006 (''[[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel US]]''), [[United Kingdom|UK]] on December 23, 2006 (''[[Discovery Channel (UK and Ireland)|Discovery Channel UK]]'') and [[Spain]] on December 25, 2006 ([[Cuatro (channel)|Cuatro]]).\n\n=== ''[[The Lost Tomb of Jesus]]'' ===\nThe documentary was co-produced and first broadcast on the [[Discovery Channel]] and [[Vision TV]] in Canada on March 4, 2007, covering the discovery of the [[Talpiot Tomb]]. It was directed by Jacobovici and produced by Felix Golubev and [[Ric Esther Bienstock]], and [[James Cameron]] served as executive producer. It was released in conjunction with a book on the same subject, ''[[The Jesus Family Tomb]]'', issued in late February 2007 and co-authored by Jacobovici and [[Charles R. Pellegrino]]. The documentary and book has claims that are disputed by some [[archaeologists]] and [[theologians]] fields as well as some linguistic and biblical scholars.\n\n=== ''[[The Naked Archaeologist]]'' ===\nThe television show was produced for [[VisionTV]] in Canada and [[History International]] in the US and was hosted and prepared by Jacobovici and [[Avri Gilad]]. The show ultimately reviewed biblical stories and then tried to find proof for them by exploring the [[Holy Land]] looking for archaeological evidence, making personal inferences and deductions and interviewing scholars and experts. After its original run on [[VisionTV]], it was picked up in the U.S. by [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]] and its sister network, [[History International]].\n\nThe episode \"A Nabatean by Any Other Name\" won the Special Jury Prize at the 8th International Archaeological Film Festival in [[Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kineon.be/Palmares-2009.html|title=List of Award Winners, 2009 Festival International du Film Archaeologique de Bruxelles|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Finding Atlantis'' ===\nJacobovici was involved as executive producer<ref>[http://www.apltd.ca/films/display/57 Finding Atlantis - Apltd.]</ref> in the production of a documentary that was shown in March 2010 on the [[National Geographic Channel]]. He claimed that [[Atlantis]] had been found in Spain, and he said that evidence found by [[University of Hartford]] Professor Richard Freund included the unearthed emblem of Atlantis and that \"[[Tarshish]] is Atlantis itself\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hartman|first=Ben|title=The deepest Jewish encampment?|url=http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=212935|accessdate=22 March 2011|newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Atlantis Rising'' ===\nIn 2016, Jacobovici directed a documentary on Atlantis for National Geographic Channel; its executive producer was James Cameron. Shot in several places in the [[Mediterranean]] ([[Greece]], [[Sardinia]], [[Malta]], [[Santorini]]) such as in Spain ([[C\u00e1diz]], [[Huelva]], [[Sevilla]], [[Ja\u00e9n, Spain|Ja\u00e9n]], [[Ciudad Real]], [[Badajoz]] and other undersea places in the [[Gulf of C\u00e1diz]]) and the [[Azores]]. It premiered on January 29, 2017 on National Geographic Channel (US)<ref>https://www.natgeotvpressroom.com/articles/show/587fc611fb8ca7dd374f3bc0</ref> and at National Geographic Spain as \"El Resurgir de la Atl\u00e1ntida\" on March 5, 2017.<ref>[https://twitter.com/NatGeoEspana/status/838249222675681280 National Geographic Espa\u00f1a: James Cameron es el productor de 'El Resurgir de la Atlantida', estreno esta tarde en NatGeo]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.apltd.ca/ Associated Producers Ltd.]\n* [http://www.apltd.ca/pages/people/simcha-jacobovici Associated Producers Ltd. - Simcha Jacobovici]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0414302|name=Simcha Jacobovici}}\n* [http://www.jesusfamilytomb.com/ Official Site for ''The Lost Tomb of Jesus'']\n* [http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/34311/canadian-director-honors-father-murdered-romanian-jews/ Simcha Jacobovici honors his father]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/thehour/video.php?id=1437 Simcha Jacobovici Interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobovici, Simcha}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Israeli descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Israeli Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:Pseudoarchaeologists]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistorians]]\n[[Category:People from Petah Tikva]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Directors of Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners for Best Documentary Film]]\n[[Category:Historical theories and materials on the Exodus]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simcha_Jacobovici"}
{"title_page": "Glassblower's cataract", "text_new": "'''Glassblower's cataracts''' are a form of [[cataract]] due to an occupational exposure. They are formed by many years or decades of exposure to [[infrared radiation]] while working in the occupation of [[glass blowing]], or working close to hot or molten metals such with [[Foundry|metal foundry workers]]<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Roberts | first1 = B. H. \n| title = A Series of Cases of \"glassblowers' Cataract\" Occurring in Chainmakers \n| journal = The British Journal of Ophthalmology \n| volume = 5 \n| issue = 5 \n| pages = 210\u2013212 \n| year = 1921 \n| pmid = 18168103 \n| pmc = 512590\n | doi=10.1136/bjo.5.5.210\n}}</ref> or [[black smith|blacksmiths]].  Glassblower's cataracts are due to chronic exposure to infrared radiation emitted due to the extreme heating of glass or molten metal. The infrared radiation is absorbed by the [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] and [[eye lens|lens]] of the eye. This causes cataracts after decades of exposure. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Geddes |first1=LA |last2=Roeder |first2=RA |year= 2006 |title= Handbook of Electrical Hazards and Accidents |url= |location= |publisher=Lawyers & Judges Publishing Company |pages=465 |isbn=978-0913875445 |edition=2nd |accessdate= }}</ref> This condition may be prevented by wearing protective glasses while practicing these occupations.[[File:Glassblowing (2377744959).jpg|thumb|Pictured here is a person [[Glassblowing]].|alt=|left|215x215px]][[File:Depiction of a person with Cataract.png|thumb|311x311px|This image shows the differences in a healthy eye versus one with a [[Cataract]].]]\n\n==  Mechanism ==\nGlassblowers tend to work with very high-temperature objects and equipment, which emit a great deal of [[infrared|infrared radiation]] through [[black-body radiation]].  The ocular lens, like all matter, has the capacity to store incident [[photon energy]] by [[resonance]] absorption. Absorption of infrared photons increases vibration of molecules, which is observed as increased temperature. Large important biomolecules such as [[protein]]s tend to lose their space structure when vibrating, known as [[Denaturation (biochemistry)|denaturation]]. The rate of protein denaturation is temperature dependent as described by the [[Arrhenius equation]]. Damage to biological tissue owing to the high rate of vibration damage is called thermal damage.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=S\u00f6derberg|first=P G|last2=Talebizadeh|first2=N|last3=Yu|first3=Z|last4=Galichanin|first4=K|date=2016-01-15|title=Does infrared or ultraviolet light damage the lens?|journal=Eye|language=En|volume=30|issue=2|pages=241\u2013246|doi=10.1038/eye.2015.266|pmid=26768915|pmc=4763141}}</ref> Prior to recent research, it was theorized that one possible mechanism was the large intake of fluid due to excessive sweating on the job. Within this theory, it was suggested that the evaporation of the sweat within the [[cornea]] \"could lead to increased concentration of the [[Aqueous humour|aqueous humou]]<nowiki/>r,\" this increase could therefore induce the cataract. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1997|title=Glassblowers' ocular health and safety: optical radiation hazards and eye protection assessment|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1475-1313.1997.0_877.x|journal=Ophthalmic and Physiological Optics|volume=17|issue=3|pages=216\u2013224|doi=10.1111/j.1475-1313.1997.0_877.x|issn=0275-5408|via=}}</ref> This however has not been proven to be true and instead it is generally accepted that the infrared photons as mentioned above are the primary cause of glassblower's cataracts.\n\n== Prevention ==\nUnfortunately, there is not one clear cut way to prevent cataracts. As this specific type of cataract is associated with occupational exposures to infrared radiation, wearing protective eye equipment while on the job or taking frequent breaks can lessen the strain on the eyes. Some modifiable common risk factors unrelated to occupation are smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, [[Vitamin E deficiency|deficiency in vitamin E]], [[Vitamin B1|B1]], and [[Vitamin B2|B2]], and increased exposure of sunlight to the eyes. Risk factors that are not modifiable include previous eye injury, family history, diabetes, the use of [[Corticosteroid|corticosteriods]], and previous eye surgery. To lessen the risk of developing cataracts it is best to limit alcohol consumption, not use or stop the use of tobacco, get adequate amounts of vitamins E, B1, and B2, and wear sunglasses and/or a wide brim hat while outside. Even if you are taking all of these steps it is still recommended that patients have eye exams every other year, or every year if over 60.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/newsletter_article/what-can-i-do-to-prevent-cataracts|title=By the way, doctor: What can I do to prevent cataracts?|last=Publishing|first=Harvard Health|website=Harvard Health|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Symptoms ==\nAs with cataracts not associated with glassblowing, symptoms typically have a gradual onset. Initially, people generally are unaware they have cataracts. Blurry vision is one of the first symptoms to appear which gradually worsens as the cataracts develop further. Colors may eventually become more and more faded, eyes will become more sensitive to light, and sometimes people will have trouble seeing at nighttime. Double vision can occur and the need to change prescriptions often are also common symptoms. Over time, vision loss can occur in people who have well developed, untreated cataracts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nei.nih.gov/learn-about-eye-health/eye-conditions-and-diseases/cataracts|title=Cataracts|last=|first=|date=August 3, 2019|website=National Eye Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n[[File:Slit lamp and binocular microscope.jpg|thumb|Pictured here is a slit lamp. When used with a [[binocular microscope]], the ophthalmologist can examine the eye with a small beam (slit) of light. The slit of light can accentuate features of the eye when directed at an angle. The microscope used in combination with the slit lamp allows for greater magnification (10 - 25 times) than typical handheld devices. ]]\nLike symptoms, glassblowers cataracts can also be diagnosed the same way as cataracts not associated with glassblowing. To diagnose cataracts, a comprehensive [[Eye examination|eye exam]] must be done. This exam will include dilation to measure the [[Pupillary response|response of the pupils]]. A [[Slit-lamp examination|slit lamp examination]] will also be conducted to examine the cornea, iris, and other areas closer to the front of the eye. A slit lamp is used because it makes it easier for [[Ophthalmology|ophthalmologists]] to spot abnormalities.  When the eye is dilated, the pupils widen so that the ophthalmologist can see the back of the eye more clearly. This is were he or she will look for signs of cataracts, [[glaucoma]], and will examine the [[retina]] and [[optic nerve]]. During this comprehensive eye exam, a [[Refraction (Ophthalmology)|refraction]] and [[Visual acuity|visual acuity test]] will also be performed. These tests assess the clarity and sharpness of a person's vision and each eye is tested individually. After combining all the data collected in this eye exam, an ophthalmologist can accurately diagnose cataracts if certain conditions are met. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aao.org/eye-health/diseases/cataracts-treatment|title=Cataract Diagnosis and Treatment|date=2019-10-01|website=American Academy of Ophthalmology|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Hinterkammerlinse 01 (fcm).jpg|left|thumb|A posterior chamber intraocular lens prior to insertion. This is inserted during cataract surgery after the cloudy eye's natural lens is removed. ]]\n\n== Treatment ==\n\nThe treatment for this condition depends on how developed the cataracts are. Early on getting a new prescription and wearing sunglasses may be all a doctor suggests. If the cataracts begin to interfere with every day life, an ophthalmologist will most likely will suggest surgery. During this surgery the clouded lens will be removed and replaced with a new, artificial lens. This lens is called an [[Intraocular lens|intraocular lens or IOL.]] The surgery itself is very safe and 9 out of 10 people who undergo this surgery can see clearer post-op. <ref name=\":0\" />\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Occupational safety and health}}\n\n[[Category:Eye]]\n[[Category:Disorders of lens]]\n[[Category:Occupational diseases]]\n", "text_old": "'''Glassblower's cataracts''' are a form of [[cataract]]. They are formed by many years or decades of exposure to [[infrared radiation]] while working in the occupation of [[glass blowing]], or working close to hot or molten metals such with [[Foundry|metal foundry workers]]<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Roberts | first1 = B. H. \n| title = A Series of Cases of \"glassblowers' Cataract\" Occurring in Chainmakers \n| journal = The British Journal of Ophthalmology \n| volume = 5 \n| issue = 5 \n| pages = 210\u2013212 \n| year = 1921 \n| pmid = 18168103 \n| pmc = 512590\n | doi=10.1136/bjo.5.5.210\n}}</ref> or [[black smith|blacksmiths]].  Glassblower's cataracts are due to chronic exposure to infrared radiation emitted due to heating of glass or molten metal. The infrared radiation is absorbed by the [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] and [[eye lens|lens]] of the eye. This causes cataracts after decades of exposure. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Geddes |first1=LA |last2=Roeder |first2=RA |year= 2006 |title= Handbook of Electrical Hazards and Accidents |url= |location= |publisher=Lawyers & Judges Publishing Company |pages=465 |isbn=978-0913875445 |edition=2nd |accessdate= }}</ref> This condition may be prevented by wearing protective glasses while practicing these occupations.[[File:Glassblowing (2377744959).jpg|thumb|Pictured here is a person [[Glassblowing]].|alt=|